:: Case Study: BLUE KETTLE [nobr]
<h1>"A Play Infected with a Virus": Signal, Noise, and the Glitch in Caryl Churchill's <i>Blue Kettle</i></h1>
<img style="max-width:100%" src="assets/imgs/blue_kettle_glitch_art_by_paul_klee.png" alt="Generated with Midjourney with prompt: 'blue kettle, glitch art, by paul klee'." title="Generated with Midjourney with prompt: 'blue kettle, glitch art, by paul klee'.">

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 1">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 1 [bk nobr] {"position":"1890,1302","size":"100,100"}
<p>[[Caryl Churchill]]‚Äôs <i>Blue Kettle</i> is one half of a pair of one-act plays first produced and performed in Edinburgh and London in 1997; it received its American premiere at the Brooklyn Academy of Music in New York on January 27th, 1999, just about one year away from the ‚Äòapocalypse‚Äô virus [[Y2K]]. The plot of <i>Blue Kettle</i> is simple: a shabby con man, Derek, tricks five different elderly women into believing that he‚Äôs the long-lost son that each of them gave up for adoption in their youth. That is, he‚Äôs discovered that each woman gave up a child when they were younger, and he pretends to be their son, for reasons obscure to both the audience and Derek himself. This plot, however, is in Churchill‚Äôs own words "a [[McGuffin]]." Churchill‚Äôs main intention towards the play, she writes in her foreword to the fourth volume of her collected drama, "was [its] destruction." <<cite "viii" "Churchill, Caryl. Churchill Plays: 4">></p>

<p>The agent of this destruction is what she calls a "[[virus]]": over the course of the play, the words that make up the dialogue begin to be replaced, with increasing frequency, with either the word "blue" or the word "kettle." This begins in the second scene, where Derek says "You don‚Äôt have to <<blue "mess">> anything up"; by the fifth scene, we have lines like "I can't <<blue "put">> it back in. What if they don‚Äôt <<blue "love">> me any <<blue "more">>?" By the end of the play, the infection is complete, and even "blue" and "kettle have been replaced by their constitutive parts: Mrs. Plant‚Äôs final line, "<span class="kettle">T</span> <span class="blue">b</span> <span class="kettle">k k k k l</span>?", is responded to, with appropriate finality, with Derek‚Äôs "<span class="blue">B</span>. <span class="kettle">K.</span>"</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 2">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 2 [bk] {"position":"1874,1452","size":"100,100"}
Contemporary reviews of the play were positive, if occasionally befuddled, but returned again and again to the metaphor of a "linguistic virus" to describe the proliferation of "<<blue blue>>" and "<<kettle kettle>>" through the dialogue - a good decade before Churchill herself used it in the aforequoted foreword. Matt Wolf‚Äôs review for American Theater states that the play "concerns the breakdown of language - words and letters as a sort of virus that by play‚Äôs end have made a mockery of meaning" <<cite "1" "Wolf, Matt. True Blue and Dreamy">>; Charles McNulty‚Äôs review for the Village Voice is titled "Language is a Virus" and suggests that "the linguistic equivalent of the [[Y2K]] virus spreads insidiously" through the play <<cite "1" "McNulty, Charles. Language is a Virus">>; and Gerard Raymond, also writing for The Village Voice, notes that Max Stafford-Clark, the play‚Äôs director, refers to the "language virus" as the heart of the play <<cite "1" "Raymond, Gerard. Play and Anti-Play">>. Contemporary criticism has been similarly invested in the metaphor of the virus, but - like the reviews - has done little to consider the metaphor‚Äôs implications.

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 3">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 3 [bk] {"position":"1874,1606","size":"100,100"}
<<define "Viruses" "virus">> can be broken up into three categories, more or less: a biological virus, like <<define "influenza">> or <<define "COVID-19">>, a computer virus, like <<define "ILOVEYOU">> or STUXNET, and a viral idea, or a <<define "meme">>. What these three sets of phenomena have in common is a focus on replication: a biological virus hijacks a cell‚Äôs machinery so that it replicates the virus rather than itself, a computer virus hijacks its host computer so that it replicates infected files, and a meme - closest to a linguistic virus - propagates and spreads across information networks via replication and both live in and constitute the minds of its hosts.
<figure>
	<img style="max-width:100%" src="assets/imgs/virus_klee.png" alt="Generated with Midjourney with prompt: 'blue, computer virus, memetic virus, virus, in the style of paul klee'." title="Generated with Midjourney with prompt: 'blue, computer virus, memetic virus, virus, in the style of paul klee'.">
	<figcaption>Generated with Midjourney with prompt: 'blue, computer virus, memetic virus, virus, in the style of paul klee'.</figcaption>
</figure>


<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 4">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 4 [bk nobr] {"position":"1873,1752","size":"100,100"}
<p>Let's focus on these technological senses rather than the biological, in part because those critics who have remarked on the figure of the virus in Churchill‚Äôs work have done so in reference to her persistent interest in genetics (her most performed play, <i>A Number</i>, is a meditation on cloning, and her play <i>[[Love and Information]]</i> has a ‚Äòscene‚Äô that‚Äôs [[nothing but a DNA sequence spoken out loud)->GENE]].  Indeed, biological replication comes up in <i>Blue Kettle</i> itself, when Derek converses with one of his marks, Mrs. Oliver, about family:</p>
<blockquote>
<span class = "script">MRS OLIVER:	Do you believe in heredity?</span><br>
<span class = "script">DEREK: 		A bit.</span><<cite "103" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">>
</blockquote>
<p>The same scene goes on, however, to discuss something closer to the memetic version of replication:</p>
<blockquote>
<span class = "script">MRS OLIVER:	But then there‚Äôs how you‚Äôre brought up. There‚Äôs family jokes.</span><br>
<span class = "script">DEREK: 	Exactly.</span><br>
<span class = "script">MRS OLIVER:	I mean I look at you and you could be anyone.<<cite "103" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">></span>
</blockquote>
<p>Thinking about "<span class="blue">blue</span> <span class = "kettle">kettle</span>" as a kind of computer virus suggests a way of reading the play with information theory - and that reading provides a provocative vocabulary for considering the mediation between sense and nonsense that the play stages. </p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 5">><</silently>>

:: Blue Kettle 5 [bk nobr] {"position":"1870,1905","size":"100,100"}
<p>This mode of informationally-informed reading, which I‚Äôm tentatively calling "literary informatics", considers the literary text as a kind of code, a bundle of information written by the author and executed by the reader. It opens up a usefully novel mode of considering the process by which the literary text becomes the phenomenological experience of the audience. </p>
<p>The naive schematic for this mode of reading is as follows: the playwright has a scene they imagine on stage. That image is transcoded, or remediated, into words, which are then printed onto the page of a script. Because exhaustively describing the full scenario to appear on stage would take pages and pages, the playwright compresses the totality of a scenario into dialogue, words on a page that are then expanded upon by the director and the actors. Sometimes there are more or less precise stage directions to guide that expansion, but <i>Blue Kettle</i> has none. R. Darren Gobart‚Äôs biological reading of the play, which focuses on DNA rather than on computer code, centers the fact that "performance provides the supplement that brings the textual DNA to theatrical life"<<cite "120" "Gobart, R. Darren. 'On Performance and Selfhood in Caryl Churchill'">>; a computational heuristic, however, foregrounds the role of the audience member in decoding and expanding the ultimate ‚Äòmessage‚Äô of the play.</p>
<figure>
<img style="max-width:75%" src="assets/imgs/informatics_schematic.png" alt="The progression of the schematic, represented visually as a papercraft author thinking, then writing, then a book, then actors on a stage, then an audience, thinking.">
<figcaption>Generated with Midjourney with various prompts and the static modifiers "papercraft" and "against a pure black background".</figcaption>
</figure>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 6">><</silently>>

:: Blue Kettle 6 [bk nobr] {"position":"1874,2046","size":"100,100"}
<p>How does that decoding take place? </p>

<p>Let‚Äôs start with the experience of reading rather than the experience of seeing the play on a stage. The initial substitutions do not significantly impede the reader‚Äôs ability to understand what‚Äôs going on; a good portion of the substitutions in the first half of the play are made wholly comprehensible in their context, either by local repetition or recognition of <<define "clich√©" "clich√©">> .</p>

<p>In the case of local repetition, one speaker will say something that‚Äôs been garbled by the virus, and their interlocutor will respond with a variation on the same sentence without its having been garbled. Importatnly, the characters understand one another‚Äôs _words_ perfectly, even if they understand one another‚Äôs (and their own) intentions but dimly. For example:</p>

<blockquote>
	<span class="script">DEREK: 	So <<blue "why">>didn‚Äôt anyone let you know?</span><br>
	<span class="script">ENID:	Why do you think?</span><<cite "105" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">>
</blockquote>

<p>Enid‚Äôs question in response to Derek‚Äôs question suggests that "blue" stands here for "why", and the sentence is intelligible as "So why didn‚Äôt anyone let you know." Redundancy preserves intelligibility - although redundancy is the first thing omitted in most digital compression algorithms. These moments, too, replicate the process by which a virus replicates: it hijacks existing text.</p>

<p>The recognition of <<define "clich√©s" "clich√©">> and idioms is another cognitive algorithm that the reader can use to decode the text. Phrases like:</p>
<blockquote>
MRS VANE: 		I burnt all the letters and the two photographs. I made a clean <<blue break>>.<<cite "108" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">>
</blockquote>
<p>and</p>
<blockquote>
MRS VANE:		That‚Äôs good. So can we fix a <<blue date>> to do that?<<cite "110" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">>
</blockquote>
<p>both invoke the reader‚Äôs familiarity with well-worn phrases to fill in the gaps. The replacement of "break" with "blue," however, defamiliarizes the clich√©, and the process of decoding the garbled language acts as a kind of productive friction that forces a reader to dwell on moments in the text that might otherwise be glossed over. Further, the specific replacements that take place - that is, ‚Äòa clean blue‚Äô for ‚Äòa clean break‚Äô - necessarily plays on whatever associations the reader has with the word ‚Äòblue‚Äô - cleanliness, water, sadness, whatever.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 7">><</silently>>

:: Blue Kettle 7 [bk] {"position":"1874,2196","size":"100,100"}
These modes of decoding, alongside things like learned <<define "genre">>-savviness from having read other plays with similar arcs and a general understanding of how conversation tends to work, makes it possible for a careful reader to, with some difficulty, pick out a signal out of the virus‚Äôs noise. An audience member has a much easier time; as most of the contemporary reviews make clear, the fact that human bodies on stage are gesticulating and emoting along with their fragmented language - and the fact that performing or reading the lines aloud requires having a sense of what words have been replaced - makes the lines‚Äô meanings much easier to comprehend. Reading the quotations aloud sends this into sharp relief.

Even by the eleventh and final scene, an exchange like: <blockquote><span class="script">DEREK: 		<<ket She Tle>> died <<ket when ket>> I <<ket ket was>> a child.</span>
<span class="script">MRS PLANT:		<<bl Is Bl>> <<bl that bl>> <<ket supposed ket>> <<bl to b>> <<bl be b>> <<bl an b>> excuse?</span>
<span class="script">DEREK:		<<ket If Ket>> <<bl you b>> like. Or not.</span><<cite "128" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">></blockquote>is mostly comprehensible.

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 8">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 8 [bk nobr] {"position":"1875,2346","size":"100,100"}
<p>That process of decoding - a sort of second kind of reading - forces the reader to translate from a language they don‚Äôt know. More intriguingly, it suggests that the translation isn‚Äôt necessary: that the particular words might not matter, and that "<<bl Is Bl>> <<bl that bl>> <<ket supposed ket>> <<bl to b>> <<bl be b>> <<bl an b>> excuse?" is instead understandable in its garbled form. The implication, then, is that words are interchangeable so long as the plots are simple enough and the meanings they‚Äôre meant to convey are common enough to infer. If the text is generically stable, then the language becomes less important; meaning operates like the <<define "Ship of Theseus">>, with successively more pieces removed without changing the text.</p>
<p>This becomes especially interesting in light of the play‚Äôs plot, <<define "McGuffin">> or not: Derek attempts, over and over again, to supplement his mother, who suffers from advanced dementia and whose dialogue, when she appears, seems to be infected with a linguistic virus of another type:</p>
<blockquote>
DEREK: I'm finding all these <<blue old>> <<kettle women>> and <<kettle pretending>> to be their long lost son.<br>
MOTHER: You didn't find me when I got lost in the garden and Mrs Molesworth says Look behind you, look behind you what could it be, what's going on behind me, I <<blue hear>> a shriek, what's behind me what's behind me.<br>
DEREK: And what was it?<br>
MOTHER: Sorry, <<blue love>>, what did you <<blue say>>?<<cite "119" "Churchill, Caryl. Blue Kettle">>
</blockquote>
<p>Derek's mother's linguistic issues are different in kind from the more general linguistic virus; she appears to be lost in distant memories and is unable to have a conversation with her son. Unlike the conversations later in the text, which can generally be followed despite the blues and the kettles, this conversation is verbally sound but lacks both sense and an emotional connection.</p>
<p>He replaces her with more emotionally available women; if he ultimately succeeds with Mrs. Plant, he does so at the expense of his words. However, if she understands him, he understands her, and we (more or less) understand both of them, that may not be much of a loss. We‚Äôre all still playing the same <<excerpt "language game." "Language Game">> Hence, perhaps, Churchill‚Äôs tongue-in-cheek admission that <i>Blue Kettle</i> was a failure as an anti-play, and that it would have succeeded only if it went on for another two scenes, staging a true-blue disintegration of meaning that neither the reader nor the audience could comprehend.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 9">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 9 [bk nobr] {"position":"1865,2502","size":"100,100"}
<p>Along those lines, we will turn to the information theoretical binary of <<define "signal" "Signal">> and <<define "noise." "Noise">></p>

<p>Let‚Äôs say I want to send a voice message to you. I take out my phone, I record the message, and I send it to you via, say, <a href = "http://m.me/kenneth.alba" target = "_blank"> Messenger</a>. What I aim for you to get is the signal - the words I‚Äôm saying or sounds I‚Äôm making. All of the extraneous stuff - the unwanted modifications that the signal suffers during capture, storage, transmission, processing, or conversion - is noise. In this context, it might be a car horn from outside, some static because of the <<define "lossy" "Loss">> compression algorithm Facebook uses for audio files in the interest of bandwidth conservation, or any number of other things.</p>

<p>The binary gets used in a much broader context online, where web forum administrators might call on-topic posts the ‚Äòsignal‚Äô and off-topic distractions ‚Äònoise‚Äô. Email spam might be thought of as noise in opposition to the Important emails that your client might tag for you. Critically, the opposition presumes both a sender and a receiver that is capable of processing information - of making ‚Äòsense‚Äô of the message, and of having an intentional stance towards that message that makes the signal meaningful and the noise meaningless. This is a distinction worth bringing up inasmuch as the language of information theory, and of technology more broadly, is often given a kind of epistemological primacy that sidesteps questions of bias and imbues its object with an aura of objectivity. </p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 10">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 10 [bk] {"position":"1865,2652","size":"100,100"}
<p>In the context of this play, then, we might think about the virus as a deliberate introduction of noise into an otherwise clear signal. As the infection grows, the signal becomes more and more muddled, until (on the page, at least) there‚Äôs nothing but noise. The cognitive work of making sense of the play is the work of noise reduction - of working around the infected language to arrive at the real, important meaning underneath. Importantly, the framework of ‚Äòsignal‚Äô and ‚Äònoise‚Äô implies just this sort of reader, one that can convert raw data into meaningful information. The signal, under this framework, is the stuff the receiver cares about; the noise is interference. That the play‚Äôs plot is merely a <<define "McGuffin">> and the virus is the point of the play, however, gestures to the provisional and contingent division of signal from noise.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 11">><</silently>>


:: Blue Kettle 11 [bk] {"position":"1865,2802","size":"100,100"}
If <i>Blue Kettle</i>'s plot is unimportant and its purpose is its own destruction, then the message being imparted from Churchill is the virus itself: in which case, the formal disintegration of the play is itself the signal, and the plot, along with the messy emotions of the characters in it, are noise that gradually clears away. I‚Äôd like to suggest that neither of these situations quite describes the play, and that the oscillation between the two - the formal experimentation and the emotional impact - is a particular aesthetic moment where the reader/audience flips between two modes of comprehending the text. The moment where signal becomes noise and vice versa is one I‚Äôd like to call the <<define "glitch" "Glitch">>, following [[Ross Menkman‚Äôs 2010 Glitch Studies Manifesto->Ross Menkman‚Äôs 2010 Glitch Studies Manifesto]]. 

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 12">><</silently>>




:: Blue Kettle 12 [bk]
I would like, however, to argue, that the aesthetic experience of the <span class="glitch" data-text="glitch">glitch</span> is not merely a binary flip of signal to noise and vice versa; instead, what interests me is the kind of limbo that the medial scenes in "Blue Kettle" put forward. Much like Kant‚Äôs description of the cognitive process of apprehending beauty in the [[Critique of Judgment]], my understanding of the <span class="glitch" data-text="glitch">glitch</span> is that moment of free-play between the attempt to distinguish meaning from the message and the experience of the image - or text - as itself, incapable of being boiled down into a coherent meaning. A sufficiently <span class="glitch" data-text="glitch">glitched</span> image gestures towards the thing that the unglitched version of the image might convey, but the visual signifiers of infection - the distortion, the lines, and so forth - are the point of the image, much like how the destruction of <i>Blue Kettle</i> is, for Churchill, the point of the play. 

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Blue Kettle 13">><</silently>>

:: Blue Kettle 13 [bk nobr]
<p>Caryl Churchill‚Äôs later work, particularly her 2012 play <i>[[Love and Information]]</i>, deals more squarely with the technological dissemination and corruption of human words and gestures via information technology, and with the potentially alienating consequences of that transmediation. The 2020s are an era where the social gestures we use to constitute ourselves in relation to one another are increasingly mediated on technological substrates, and where the words we use are increasingly infected with viral language from Twitter and so forth. As Patricia Lockwood puts it in her essay about the Internet titled "The Communal Mind":</p>
<blockquote>But worth remembering: the mind had been, in its childhood, a place of play.<br>
It had also once been the place where you sounded like yourself. Gradually it had become the place where we sounded like each other, through some erosion of wind or water on a self not nearly as firm as stone.<br><<cite "*" "Lockwood, Patricia. The Communal Mind.">>
</blockquote>
<p>Calvin Kasulke's 2021 novel <i>Several People Are Typing</i> explores similar territory; an epistolary novel set in a workplace's Slack server, it features a plotline where emojis - and, eventually, fragments of <<define "emojis" "emoji">> - replace language altogether, culminating in two characters breaking off a relationship thusly:</p>
<blockquote>
tripp<br>
:bsup: :sup: :th:<br>
:th:<br>
:st: :y-: :y-: :y-:<br>
:y-: :y-:<br>
:y:<br>
<br>
Beverley<br>
Don‚Äôt be dramatic.<br>
I‚Äôm not being hurtful, I‚Äôm expressing regret. I‚Äôm not blaming you for anything.<br>
<br>
tripp<br>
:y-: :sti: :y-:<br>
:y-: :y-: :-:<br>
[...]<br>
Beverly<br>
We're done, Tripp. Okay?<br>
<br>
tripp<br>
:-:<br>
:-:<br>
:thumb:<<cite "228" "229" "Kasulke, Calvin. Several People Are Typing.">>
</blockquote>
<p>Churchill‚Äôs exploration of a "language virus" in <i>Blue Kettle</i> suggests a potential form of resistance: by flipping the script, and by reconsidering what is signal and what is noise in the messages we receive, we can reconsider the contingencies inherent in the technologies that‚Äôre transmitting those messages. In the same way that "Blue Kettle" forces the reader to ‚Äòdecode‚Äô the semantic content of a phrase denuded of meaningful signifiers, we can reconsider and try to decode the content of language that we - and others - use that‚Äôs become totally infected with commonplace viral language - the "sames", emojis, "big moods" and "on brands" of living in the information age.</p>

