	</figure>


<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 2">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 2 [mrbb nobr]

<p>Sturdyvant expects trouble from Rainey: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt care what she calls herself,‚Äù he hollers at Irvin, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not putting up with it. I just want to get her in here ‚Ä¶ record those songs on that list ‚Ä¶ and get her out. Just like <<define "clockwork">>, huh?‚Äù <<cite "18" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">>. When Rainey ultimately arrives, however - after the white men, her band, and the play‚Äôs audience has been waiting for about an hour  - she‚Äôs anything but clockwork. Whereas Sturdyvant wants a singing automaton he can record and sell, Rainey is defiantly and powerfully a human body from the moment she fills the stage.</p>
<p>	Wilson plays with this technologic/organic binary throughout the play: a technological whiteness, represented primarily by Sturdyvant, obsessed with clock-time and allied with the recording process, against a stubbornly embodied blackness, represented primarily although not exclusively by Rainey, who Wilson identifies with live performance and with the ‚Äòreal‚Äô blues.</p>
<p>The play stages a power struggle between these two poles, with Rainey insisting on her own bodiliness in the face of Sturdyvant and Irvin‚Äôs attempt to transmute her voice into a valuable commodity. Although this binary makes for compelling drama and speaks to the history of (largely white) exploitation of black musicians, it fails to capture the degree to which the historical Rainey took ownership of the recording technology that made her a household name - and threatens to renaturalize a rhetoric that equates blackness with an atavistic, primitive ‚Äòsoulfulness.‚Äô This section will begin, then, by sketching out how Wilson stages this binary, before problematizing it with reference to the historical Rainey‚Äôs own stage show and to Wilson‚Äôs own words outside of the playtext.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 3">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 3 [mrbb nobr]

<p>Through most of the play Sturdyvant is in a control-box, physically alienated from the recording session, and his commands come through a speaker in the recording studio. In contrast to Rainey, for whom lived experience is paramount, Sturdyvant‚Äôs speech suggests a subjectivity obsessed with <<define "clock-time" "clockwork">>. As I noted earlier, he wants the session to go ‚Äúlike clockwork;‚Äù when Rainey is late, he asks Irvin ‚ÄúDo you know what time it is? Have you looked at the clock?‚Äù <<cite "47" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">>, and when Rainey wants to stop the session for her coca-cola, he tells her ‚ÄúWait just a minute, Ma ‚Ä¶ you come in an hour late ‚Ä¶ we‚Äôre way behind schedule as it is.‚Äù Indeed, it‚Äôs easy to read Slow Drag‚Äôs declaration that ‚Äúthe white man don‚Äôt know how to have a good time" <<cite "41" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">> as an indictment of Sturdyvant‚Äôs technologized obsession with the clock. Sturdyvant himself, then, can be read as the clockwork man that he wants to make Rainey into, having thoroughly internalized a mechanized, penny-pinching, second-counting mode of living.</p>
	<figure>
		<img style="width:75%" src="assets/imgs/mr_clockworkman.png">
		<figcaption>Generated with Midjourney with prompt: 'a clockwork man in a 1920s recording studio, against a pure black background, in the style of Paul Klee'.</figcaption>
	</figure>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 4">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 4 [mrbb nobr]

<p>Conversely, Ma Rainey‚Äôs recalcitrance throughout the recording session refers repeatedly back to her body. We‚Äôre told early in the play that she complained during a previous session of her sore throat. This time around, she starts by lambasting Sturdyvent for keeping the studio too cold:</p>
<blockquote>MA RAINEY: Why you all keep it so cold in here? Sturdyvant try and pinch every penny he can. You all wanna make some records, you better put some heat on in here or give me back my coat‚Äù <<cite "53" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">>.</blockquote>
<p>And although her throat‚Äôs fine this time around, she stops the recording session when she realizes that she hasn‚Äôt been given a bottle of Coca-Cola. In each case, she exerts control over the recording session by insisting upon her status as an embodied human being, with bodily urges and preferences. Hence her stated preference for live performance over recordings; when Irvin protests against Ma Rainey having her stuttering nephew Sylvester perform the spoken introduction to her song, she replies to his "Ma, we don't have time" with:</p>
<blockquote>If you wanna make a record, you gotta find time. I aint' playing with you, Irvin. I can walk out of here and go back to my tour. I got plenty fans. I don't need to go through all of this. Just go and get the boy a microphone <<cite "74" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom">>.</blockquote> 
<p>Here Rainey directly mobilizes her body - threatening to <i>walk</i> out to her embodied tour - to take control over the microphone as a tool of the recording process.</p>
<p>What Irvin and Sturdyvant's <<define "apparatus">> aims to capture, though, is some version of Ma Rainey that is outside of and separate from her body, a disembodied voice that the technological apparatus means to capture - as Rainey says, all they want is to take her "voice and trap it in them fancy boxes with all them buttons and dials" <<cite "78" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom">>. Rainey's attitude towards the technology of recording is dismissive and uninterested; she reduces the operations of the recording apparatus to gnomic "buttons and dials" while dialing in on the far more important, coercive power dynamics at play. Rainey's voice comes from her body, and her blues come from her body, and she uses that body and that voice to exert power over the recording process.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 5">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 5 [mrbb nobr]
<p>Rainey's power is contested and contained by the technological exploitation of Sturdyvant and his ilk; where Rainey, standing barefoot in the studio, has control, the black members of her backing band do not. Consider Levee who thinks himself a keen observer of the power dynamics of the recording studio. When he insists that the band practice and perform <i>his</i> version of "Ma Rainey's Black Bottom", he does so by aligning himself with Sturdyvant and Irvin's recording technology:</p>
<blockquote>Ma's the boss on the road! We at a recording session. Mr. Sturdyvant and Mr. Irvin say what's gonna be here! <<cite "37" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">></blockquote>
<p>And unlike Rainey, Levee prefers the technological embrace of the studio over live performance; he dismisses the tour as "tent-show nonsense" <<cite "65" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">></p>
<p>But Levee's understanding of his relationship with the power of recording technology is fundamentally flawed. We never see "Ma Rainey's Black Bottom" recorded in the play; although Sylvester successfully performs the spoken intro and Rainey sings the song (her way), Levee accidentally kicks (with his fancy new shoes!) the microphone plug out and the take is lost. This failure prefigures Levee's unsuccessful attempts later in the play to exert power over Sturdyvant, who buys off his songs for five dollars and leaves him powerless. Levee's immediate response to this loss of power is a violent explosion at Toledo, who scuffs Levee's shoe accidentally. Where Rainey uses her body and her voice to control the recording session, Levee's body gets in the way, with fatal consequences.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 6">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 6 [mrbb nobr]

<p>Rainey's references to her body makes sense because the blues she sings are inextricable from her corporeal self.  The first song that the audience sees her sing is a verse of "Those Dogs of Mine,‚Äù a song about her aching feet, after removing her shoes and rubbing her soles.</p>
<figure>
	<video controls>
	<source src="assets/videos/mr_tdom.mp4" type="video/mp4">
	Your browser does not support the video tag.
	</video>
	<figcaption>"Those Dogs Of Mine" was recorded in 1924 by the historical Ma Rainey and released by Paramount Records. This recording is in the public domain.</figcaption>
</figure>
<blockquote>
Out for a walk, I stopped to talk<br>
Oh, how my corns did burn<br>
I had to keep on the shady side of the street<br>
To keep out the light of the sun<br>
<br>
Oh, Lord, these dogs of mine<br>
They sure do worry me all the time<br>
The reason why, I don't know<br>
Sometimes I soak 'em in Sapolio <<cite "249" "Davis, Angela. Blues Legacies and Black Feminism.">>
</blockquote>
<p>Unlike Levee, who needs his shoes to successfully perform his masculinity, Rainey records her music barefoot.</p>
<p>Similarly, the title song, ‚ÄúMa Rainey‚Äôs Black Bottom,‚Äù refers to a dance, but is also a reference to Rainey‚Äôs own (sexual) body:</p>
<blockquote> Want to see the dance you call the black bottom<br>
I wanna learn that dance<br>
Want to see the dance you call your big black bottom<br>
That puts you in a trance<br>
<br>
All the boys in the neighborhood<br>
They say your black bottom is really good<br>
Come on and show me your black bottom<br>
I wanna learn that dance <<cite "231" "232" "Davis, Angela. Blues Legacies and Black Feminism.">>
</blockquote>
<p>This focus on the body is not atypical for the blues; unlike most other popular music of their era, the blues deviated in their "provocative and pervasive sexual -- including homosexual -- imagery" <<cite "3" "Davis, Angela. Blues Legacies and Black Feminism.">>. While not all of Rainey's music is focused on her body, Wilson's selection of songs that identify her music with her corporeal self highlights the difference between her and Sturdyvant, and sets up an oppositional relationship between her black body and the white technology of the recording studio. As Alan Nadel writes, Rainey‚Äôs ‚Äúsinging isn‚Äôt something already formed but something formed in the act‚Äù <<cite "16" "Nadel, Alan. May All Your Fences Have Gates.">> - or in Rainey‚Äôs own words, that the blues are ‚Äúlife‚Äôs way of talking [...] you sing ‚Äòcause that‚Äôs a way of understanding life‚Äù <<cite "86" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">>.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 7">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 7 [mrbb nobr]
<p>	According to this reading, then, Ma Rainey represents the blues - and blackness - as lived, embodied experience against a technologized whiteness that severs Ma Rainey‚Äôs music from its context, creating the disjunction of information from its temporo-spatial context that is endemic of <<define "transcoding">> more broadly and that echoes the historical violence perpetrated against African-Americans throughout the history of America.</p>
<p>This contrast is most vivid in Rainey‚Äôs figuration of the recording process as one of sexual violation:</p>
<blockquote>They don't care nothing about me. All they want is my voice. Well, I done learned that, and they gonna treat me like I want to be treated no matter how much it hurt them... As soon as they get my voice down on them recording machines, then it‚Äôs just like if I‚Äôd be some whore and they roll over and put their pants on. <<cite "79" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">></blockquote> 
<p>Rainey‚Äôs simile recalls a history of white sexual violence against and exploitation of black female bodies, invoked elsewhere in the play through Levee‚Äôs story about his mother‚Äôs rape, but it also symbolically links her music with her sexualized body. Rainey has power in the recording studio because of her voice, and because she doesn't <i>need</i> to record her music to succeed. Again, she prefers live performance, telling Irvin that he can either record her music her way or she can "carry [her] black bottom on back down South to my tour, 'cause [she] don't like it up here no ways" <<cite "63" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom">>.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 8">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 8 [mrbb nobr]
<p>Wilson's play sketches out this opposition cleanly and consistently, but the particularity of the technologies in question, along with an examination of the historical Rainey's own live concerts, demonstrates how Rainey herself deconstructed this binary in her larger-than-life performance.</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs first think about the particularity of the vinyl record as the medium onto which Rainey is being recorded, and through which Rainey will be disseminated. One trend we see as recording technology progresses is a moving window of <<define "nostalgia" "Nostalgia">>. The earliest example of this may be the discussion of writing in Plato‚Äôs <i>Phaedrus</i>, which Socrates worries will:</p>
<blockquote> ...introduce forgetfulness into the soul of those who learn it: they will not practice using their memory because they will put their trust in writing, which is external and depends on signs that belong to others, instead of trying to remember from the inside.<<cite "*" "Plato. Phaedrus.">></blockquote>
<p>Lived experience, by this account, has an <span class="glow">aura</span> that dissipates when committed to paper via writing - we might think, here, of the rest of the band‚Äôs accusing Toledo‚Äôs of literacy getting him to the point where he has forgotten ‚Äúhow to laugh and have a good time. Just like the white man‚Äù <<cite "42" "Wilson, August. Ma Rainey's Black Bottom.">>.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 9">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 9 [mrbb nobr]
<p>In the contemporary moment, however, vinyl records and other analog technology has itself acquired a (not unproblematic) nostalgic premium; see, for example, the discussion - by two white kids - of blues records in Hari Kunzru‚Äôs <i>White Tears</i> - the digital is ‚Äúout of touch with the human body‚Äù and lacks ‚Äúthe soul, the vibration of an animal-gut string, the resonance of lacquered rosewood‚Äù. In contrast with <<define "noiseless" "noise">>, <<define "lossless" "loss">> digital technology, the analog record, with its snaps, pops, and scratches, attests to its own historicity as an object that has travelled through time and demands a social relation between its recorder and its auditor.</p>
<p>There are echoes of this in Wilson‚Äôs description, during 1988 interview with Bill Moyers, of the first time he listened to the blues:</p>
<figure>
	<video id="wilson_on_blues" controls>
	<source src="assets/videos/wilson_on_blues.mp4" type="video/mp4">
	Your browser does not support the video tag.
	</video>
	<figcaption>August Wilson being interviewed by Bill Moyers in 1988.</figcaption>
	<script>
	document.getElementById("wilson_on_blues").currentTime = 249;
	</script>
</figure>
<blockquote>
	AUGUST WILSON: [...] I used to collect 78 records that I would buy from the St Vincent de Paul store, at five cents apiece, and I did this indiscriminately [....] And one day in my sack of records there was a yellow-labeled record that had a typewritten label, which was kind of odd. And I put it on, and it was ‚ÄùNobody in Town Can Bake a Sweet Jelly Roll Like Mine.‚Äù It was by Bessie Smith, of course, and I listened to it, and I had one of those old 78s where you had to keep putting the needle in, and I recall I listened to the record 22 straight times. I had never in my life  -- [...] And just over and, you know. I had never heard anything like it ‚Äî and I was literally stunned by its beauty. [...] And it spoke ‚Äì there was an immediate emotional response.<br>
	BILL MOYERS: What did it say?<br>
	AUGUST WILSON: Well, it was someone speaking directly to me.<<cite "*" "Moyers, Bill, and August Wilson.">>
</blockquote>

<p>Wilson‚Äôs description is intensely physical: he begins by describing the material conditions surrounding his finding Bessie Smith‚Äôs record, describes the ‚Äúodd‚Äù label,‚Äù and talks about the experience of having to put the needle down on the record twenty-two straight times. His response, too, is both physical and emotional - he‚Äôs ‚Äúliterally stunned‚Äù by its beauty; the record ‚Äúspeaks directly to him,‚Äù and he has an ‚Äúimmediate emotional response.‚Äù The technological apparatus makes possible the very kind embodied experience that, in the play, it opposes.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 10">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 10 [mrbb nobr]
<p>In the same interview, Wilson talks about the blues as an information communication technology itself, as a ‚Äúphilosophical system at work,‚Äù a ‚Äúway of passing along information,‚Äù where the music provides an emotional context not unlike the <span class="glow"><<define "Benjaminian aura" "Benjamin's aura">></span> for the information that the song contains. Rather than reifying the opposition between white technology and black embodiedness, as I‚Äôve argued that <i>Ma Rainey‚Äôs Black Bottom</i> threatens to do, Wilson here instead argues that the blues functioned as its own of discourse network whose message was that ‚Äúthere [is] a nobility to the lives of blacks in America.‚Äù<<cite "*" "Moyers, Bill, and August Wilson.">></p>
<p>And those recordings make it possible for us, too, to listen to the voice of Gertrude Rainey, who died at the age of 53 in 1939. Like photography, phonography is an elegiac art; to paraphrase Susan Sontag, all phonographs are <i>memento mori</i>, and testify to time's relentless melt. <<cite "15" "Sontag, Susan. On Photography.">> Writing specifically about the recorded voice, Friedrich Kittler notes that all phonographic recordings are always already posthumous, and that when a record is played it is always "a corpse that speaks" <<cite "83" "Kittler, Friedrich. Gramophone, Film, Typewriter.">>. The record is <<define "nostalgic" "Nostalgia">> by nature, but the undead voice can speak with startling vitality.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 11">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 11 [mrbb nobr]
<p>In ‚ÄúStaging the Blues,‚Äù Paige McGinley recounts a secondhand description of one of the historical Ma Rainey's live performances:</p>
<blockquote>Collectively, the audience began to call out, "The Phantuuhm." [...] The call referred to Rainey herself. Her presence was duly conjured by the Wildcats Jazz Band's instrumental blues and the audience's enthused chant: "The Phaaaaantuhm! The Phaaaaaantuhm!" The curtain rose, revealing a giant prop replica of a Victrola; a chorus dancer began to play a similarly outsized prop record on the phonograph. From inside the Victrola, not yet visible to spectators, Rainey began to sing her wildly popular ‚ÄúMoonshine Blues,‚Äù [...] At a climactic moment in the song, she emerged from the boxy set piece, glittering in a famously extravagant gown and jewels, to the great delight of her audience.<<cite "31" "McGinley, Paige. Staging the Blues.">></blockquote>
<p>Whereas Wilson‚Äôs Rainey sets up an opposition between her records and her touring - privileging the latter - the real Rainey brought the record onto the stage. The historical Gertrude "Ma" Rainey refused to identify the technological with whiteness and instead claimed it as a part of her own show. Rainey‚Äôs success as a recording artist meant that much of her audience would already have heard her voice in their own homes; her stage performance suggests that she embraced the reach and the popularity that the then-novel technology gave her, collapsing the distance Wilson imagines between the embodied and the technological. This does not, of course, undo the fundamentally exploitative relationship that existed between Rainey and her white producers at Paramount ‚ÄúRace‚Äù Records, any more than Rainey‚Äôs choice of a painted cotton field as a backdrop for her live shows undoes the violence of slavery. It does, however, demonstrate how Rainey, as a savvy stage performer in her own right, made use of the very technology that Sturdyvent hopes will make her superfluous.</p>
<p>And the call that "conjured" her, for "the Phantuhm", suggests a similar savviness to the way that the phonograph can only ever record a ghost, and that the voice that Sturdyvant and his machine captures is, at best, an echo.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Ma Rainey 12">><</silently>>

:: Ma Rainey 12 [mrbb nobr]
<p>By reading Wilson‚Äôs play alongside his--and Rainey‚Äôs--own history, then, we can see that the conflict isn‚Äôt necessarily between a technology which is essentially white and a body that is essentially black; instead, the problem in <i>Ma Rainey‚Äôs Black Bottom</i> is historically contingent. Sturdyvent controls the recording apparatus, and Sturdyvent is exploitative, but the product-the record-is ultimately Rainey‚Äôs, available for a young Wilson to pick out of a bin and draw inspiration from years later. Rainey‚Äôs stage performance suggests how black music has functioned, in Louis Chude-Sokei‚Äôs words, as ‚Äúthe primary space of direct black interaction with technology and informatics‚Äù <<cite "5" "Chude-Sokei, Louis. The Sound of Culture.">>, and that the utilization of that technology makes possible the sort of emotional encounter, disjointed in time and space, whose absence Benjamin mourns and that Wilson, in the aforementioned interview, credits as so instrumental to his development as a playwright.</p>

