:: Section 1 Conclusions [nobr]
I don't want to jump to conclusions here, so I won't, but eventually I'm sure to arrive at some.

:: Case Study: HER STORY {"position":"1740,1152","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Texts, Interfaces, and the Puzzle Element in <i>Her Story</i></h1>

<figure>
	<img style="max-width:75%" src="assets/imgs/hs_cover_image.jpg" alt="Her Story: A Game About A Woman Talking To The">
	<figcaption>Note: if you haven't played the game yet, you should. You can find it <a href="https://www.herstorygame.com" target="_blank">here</a>.</figcaption>
</figure>
<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 1">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 1 [hs nobr]
<p><i>Her Story</i> is an interactive film wrapped in a <<define "database" "Database">>. The film is a series of seven police interviews, chopped up into 3 to 200 second clips, of a woman who has been accused of murder. The film can only be watched by typing in search queries, and the database returns only the first five videos, in the chronology of the film-world, that contain the query typed in. The player pieces together the mystery at the heart of the game in whatever order they choose ‚Äì the primary cue that the game provides is an initial search term, <span class= "definition-link"><<link "MURDER">><<murder>><</link>></span>, ‚Äì and the game is ‚Äòover‚Äô only when the player decides they have seen enough.</p>

<figure>
	<img style="max-width:100%" src="assets/imgs/hs_murder.png" alt="The starting screen of 'Her Story'.">
	<figcaption>When the user starts the game, the search term "murder" is pre-filled, and they can view four videos where the word "murder" occurs.</figcaption>
</figure>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 2">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 2 [hs nobr]
<p>There‚Äôs much to admire about <i>Her Story</i> ‚Äì Viva Seifert‚Äôs performance is terrific, the writing is sharp and engaging, and the story itself is extremely compelling. I‚Äôd like, however, to dwell on the <<define "interface" "Interface">> ‚Äì how the player accesses the clips themselves ‚Äì and think about how that use of loss and absence creates, paradoxically, a sense of <<define "presence">> for the player. In the game, <<define "UI">> and <<define "UX">> design provides a site for the rediscovery of the author in the wake of their <<define "much-ballyhooed death" "death of the author">>.</p>

<figure>
	<video controls>
	<source src="assets/videos/hs_readme.mp4" type="video/mp4">
	Your browser does not support the video tag.
	</video>
	<figcaption>The game's readme file, embedded within the obsolete LOGIC system, is situated as a help file for an interface designed to help detectives trawling through evidence.</figcaption>
</figure>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 3">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 3 [hs nobr]
<p><<define "Loss">>, which Lev Manovich identified as a major feature of so-called 'new media' almost 20 years ago, informs the game‚Äôs interface design. Although the game does have <<define "non-diegetic">> music and the clips have <<define "diegetic">> audio, the main aural input is ambient; the fluorescent lights visible in reflection on the simulated CRT screen of the game buzz and sputter, typing in search queries clatters like a mechanical keyboard, and the fans and hard disks of the decrepit, simulated computer audibly hum.  Thus the audio cues create three separate levels of reality: the world of the video clips, the world of the person accessing the video clips, in the fluorescent-lit room, and the world of the player.</p>
<p>Indeed, in an <a target="_blank" href="assets/pdfs/app_unwrapper_interview.pdf">interview</a>, Barlow noted exactly that separation as the purpose of the non-diegetic music:</p>
<blockquote>The music was one of those things that was there to cut through the experience and create a little bit of separation between the ‚Äòworld of the game‚Äô and the world of the player ‚Äì important in establishing that there‚Äôs a difference.</blockquote>
<figure>
	<img style="max-width:75%" src="assets/imgs/hs_diagram_1.png" alt="A frame from one of the recorded videos in Her Story.">
	<figcaption>The first level: the audiovideo recording of Viva Seifart's character in police custody.</figcaption>
</figure>

<figure>
	<img style="max-width:75%" src="assets/imgs/hs_diagram_2.png" alt="A monitor frame containing the LOGIC interface.">
	<figcaption>The second level: an old monitor with an obsolete, fictional operating system. The user can hear the occasional click of a mouse or flicker of a flourescent light bulb.</figcaption>
</figure>

<figure>
	<img style="max-width:75%" src="assets/imgs/hs_diagram_3.png" alt="A Macbook Pro with a screenshot containing Her Story, along with other stuff in the background.">
	<figcaption>The third level: the player of the game on a modern laptop, with nondiegetic music cues.</figcaption>
</figure>
<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 4">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 4 [hs nobr]
<p><i>Her Story's</i> interface more generally situates itself as an obsolete police database, called LOGIC, that‚Äôs been made accessible to the player character as a result of a Freedom of Information request. Time has not been kind to the database. The videos themselves have been artificially aged to look like old VHS tapes, providing another layer of loss and <<define "noise">> beyond the CRT. Additionally, the order of the clips has disappeared (although timestamps appear in each video, making reassembly possible), and (most importantly) the transcript of the interviews through which the player trawls is itself inaccessible, visible only in closed-caption snippets on each clip (a brief note, signed by "SB," ‚Äì short for Sam Barlow? - says that the detective‚Äôs other tapes were lost in a flood in 1997).</p>

<figure>
	<img style="max-width:75%" src="assets/imgs/hs_really_readme.png" alt="A still screen from Her Story with the readme described above..">
	<figcaption>This file, "REALLY_readme!!!!.txt, makes it clear that the player's avatar is not a police detective but instead a different character, who is revealed to be Sarah, the daughter / niece of the interviewees.</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>The content, like the interface, is conditioned by losses that imbue these digital video clips with an <span class="glow"><<define "aura">></span>.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 5">><</silently>>


:: Her Story 5 [hs nobr]
<p>Those fluorescent lights outline the starkest instance of this operative absence, which became clear for me, at least, only upon my discovery of the "anti-glare filter" buried in LOGIC‚Äôs settings. Once the player activates the anti-glare filter, the fluorescent lights disappear; it is only after having done so that it becomes obvious that they were there the whole time, and ‚Äì more importantly ‚Äì that they were broken up by the ghostly silhouette of the player character ‚Äì a silhouette that matches the player themselves. Thus the player's <<define "avatar" "Avatar">> becomes visible when rendered invisible by the anti-glare feature.</p>

<figure>
	<video controls>
	<source src="assets/videos/hs_filter.mp4" type="video/mp4">
	Your browser does not support the video tag.
	</video>
	<figcaption>Toggling the "anti-glare" filter disables the nostalgic trappings of the CRT monitor and calls attention to the situatedness of the player's avatar.</figcaption>
</figure>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 6">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 6 [hs nobr]
<p>If the user never discovers the anti-glare feature, then they become aware of their avatar's reflection at specific moments of discovery within the game. Occasional light effects in the play-world of Susan make her reflection more visible. Although the precise logic governing these light effects is difficult to pinpoint, numerous players have reported that it occurs when a particular pivotal discovery is made: for example, that Viva Siefert is playing not one but two women, or that these two women are identical twins.</p>

<figure>
	<video controls>
	<source src="assets/videos/hs_twin_siren.mp4" type="video/mp4">
	Your browser does not support the video tag.
	</video>
	<figcaption>After the pivotal discovery that Hannah and Eve are twins, an offscreen siren makes the player's avatar's reflection more visible.</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>This moment of recognition works alongside the piece‚Äôs general concern with mirrors and reflections. The central mystery involves a doppelganger, the murder victim worked at a glazier‚Äôs and made <<define "mirrors" "mirror">> for a living, the interviewee's names are both palindromic (Hannah and Eve), and the murder weapon is ultimately a shard of a mirror. The player sees Susan's face as a reflection of their own, positioned on the screen in such a way that her face mirrors the player's own; one needn't (and probably shouldn't) jump to Lacan to explore how this creates a robust <<define "apparatus">> for identification.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 7">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 7 [hs nobr]
<p>The moment of recognition is emphasized by the nested structure of the game, where the player is encouraged by the interface to identify first with the detective interrogating the woman, then with the person in front of the database ‚Äì Sarah ‚Äì and in a few particularly clever moments, where the results of a search query seem to address a prurient gamer rather than the detective, with themselves as a player.</p>

<figure>
	<video controls>
	<source src="assets/videos/hs_sexlife.mp4" type="video/mp4">
	Your browser does not support the video tag.
	</video>
	<figcaption>The first clip that surfaces when the player searches for "sex" is an admonition: "Really? You're going to ask me about my sex life? Isn't that private?"</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>The player receives a similar admonition when they search for the keyword "twin", though that one is more misleading than sincere; the "twin" hypothesis seems the most plausible, according to my reading, in a way that sidesteps some familiar problems with multiple personality disorders in narrative.</p>

<p>These moments recall some of the best parts of other games, where the player is abruptly thrown from the distant position of player-controlling-an-avatar into a character within the game world; for example, in the horror-cum-dating-sim <i><<define "Doki Doki Literature Club">></i>, when the antagonist Monika shifts from addressing the user as the name they provided at the start of the game and, by digging through files on the player's computer, refers to them instead by their real name. Interface establishes relationships between subjects and objects, and games are uniquely suited to have moments that operate transdiegetically, that grab the player by their shirt and pull them through the screen.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 8">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 8 [hs nobr] 
<p>The game's absent transcript pushes that transdiegetic identification in part because it is in many players‚Äô experience (including my own) supplemented by another player-generated one: a notepad where the player starts to outline the murder at the center of the game. Because the game has no set path, the player has to investigate, and investigation here means keeping track of names, places, and important objects. I ended up with a four-page web of connections, with notes on each node. Adam Smith, of Rock Paper Shotgun, cited a similar experience in his review:</p>
<blockquote>I have three pages of notes, tracking events, cross-referencing details, picking out contradictions. It‚Äôs a dissection of life based on assumptions that seem inevitable and insights that are mine and mine alone.<<cite "*" "Smith, Adam. Wot I Think: Her Story.">></blockquote>
<p>The notebook, here, functions alongside the game itself as a <<define "cognitive prosthesis" "prosthetic">> to create a system of texts and player which both extends the game interface out into the world and interpolates the player into the gameworld.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 9">><</silently>>


:: Her Story 9 [hs nobr]
<p>This system can be provocatively described, I think, as what N. Katherine Hayles calls a <<define "cognitive assemblage">>:</p>
<blockquote>tighter or looser collections of technical objects and human participants through which cognitions circulate in the form of information, interpretations, and meanings.<<cite "10" "Hayles, N. Katherine. Writing Posthuman: The Literary Text as Cognitive Assemblage.">></blockquote> 
<p>The kinds of identification that an interface like that of <i>Her Story</i> ‚Äì with its punctum of pad of paper, along with its funhouse of nested reflections, making porous the boundary between self and screen ‚Äì gives rise to a different kind of "reading" subject that <<define "extends the mind" "extended mind">> across multiple platforms. The <<define "cognition">> imbricated in untangling <i>Her Story</i>'s mysteries takes place at multiple levels, on multiple platforms; for someone like Hayles, this creates a truly <<define "posthuman">> subject, a kind of <<define "cyborg">> that's less science fiction and more grounded in contemporary reality.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 10">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 10 [hs nobr]
<p>This subject, stretched between paper, screen, and keyboard, uniquely arises because of the game's <<define "multimedial">> and <<define "heterogeneric">> structure, which many of the game's contemporary reviewers commented on. The Washington Post's Michael Thomsen called <i>Her Story</i> a "beautiful amalgam of the cinema and video game formats [that] wouldn't work as a linear film" <<cite "*" "Thomsen, Micahel. 'Her Story' Review'">>, or that <i>Polygon</i>‚Äôs Colin Campbell proclaimed <i>Her Story</i> the best video game of 2015 by saying "I don‚Äôt think you will ‚Äòread‚Äô a better mystery novel this year" <<cite "*" "Kollar, Philip. Polygon's 2015 Games of the Year #1: Her Story">>.

<p>This last is a provocative statement. Other critics, particularly Emily Short, have effectively gestured towards Her Story‚Äôs mining of Gothic tropes. Short writes:</p>

<blockquote>it's a Gothic story, fundamentally, the bones of Radcliffe and Bronte still visible under the wrappings of more modern genres. The duality of persons, the midwife, the poison, the significant pictures that are usually kept covered up; the obsession with mirrors and fairy-tales, doppelgangers and disguises, the forbidden places within the home, the family secrets preserved by servants, the false parentage. <<cite "*" "Short, Emily. Her Story, Further Reflections">></blockquote>

<p>While I do not disagree with Short's assessment, I'd like to shift our focus to a <<define "genre">> which is a neighbor of the Gothic: detective fiction.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 11">><</silently>>

:: Her Story 11 [hs nobr]
<p>Charles Rzepka defines detective fiction as featuring four elements: a detective, a mystery, an investigation, and ‚Äì most usefully and intruigingly for those of us interested in interactive narrative ‚Äì what Rzepka calls the "puzzle element." Rzepka defines the "puzzle element" as:</p>

<blockquote>the presentation of the mystery as an ongoing problem for the reader to solve, and its powers to engage the reader‚Äôs own reasoning abilities.<<cite "10" "Rzepka, Charles. Detective Fiction.">></blockquote> 

<p>Those stories wherein the puzzle element directly engages the reader‚Äôs attention and powers of inference are, for him, "detective fiction," or "stories of detection" as distinguished from a mystery story, which may lack the puzzle element.</p>

<p>But the puzzle element in Her Story isn‚Äôt there to make the player identify with the actual detective; in fact, several moments in the game give the detective specific traits that alienate them from the player. We learn, for example, that the detective has red hair and children. The real ‚Äòdetective‚Äô in Her Story is Sarah, whose ghostly silhouette reflects the player's face, and her motive isn‚Äôt determining innocence or guilt; it‚Äôs figuring out who her mother is, and, in "SB"‚Äôs words at the ‚Äòend‚Äô of the game, to "understand why your mother did what she did."</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 12">><</silently>>


:: Her Story 12 [hs nobr]
<p>It is possible, then, to identify (as Emily Short does, in her longer meditation on the game) with Eve and with Hannah. This identification is most interesting, however, through Sarah ‚Äì identifying with a character who is identifying with someone else. The lossy interface here thematizes this identification as well, with VHS distortion and a clunky search function operating as a proxy for the temporal distance that separates mother from daughter. This reading twists the title of the work, with <i>Her</i> growing to refer not to Hannah and Eve but instead to Sarah. These kinds of technologically ‚Äì and specifically videotape - mediated relationships between parent and child make up a familiar trope; consider, as a node for comparison, the relationship between Prairie and Frenesi Gates in Thomas Pynchon‚Äôs <i>Vineland</i>, between Hal and James Incandenza in David Foster Wallace‚Äôs <i>Infinite Jest</i>, or between Nell and Miranda in Neal Stephenson's <i>The Diamond Age</i>.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Her Story 13">><</silently>>


:: Her Story 13 [hs nobr] {"position":"1747,3028","size":"100,100"}
<i>Her Story</i> is at turns alienating and interpolating, in a genre that was interactive long before it was electronic, and the kinds of identification it creates are complex, often shocking, and masterfully executed through its interface. In a contemporary moment where so many of our own social gestures are mediated technologically, dislocated radically in time and in space, the kinds of identification that Her Story‚Äôs interface makes possible are worth consideration.

