The past two decades have seen an explosion of methodologies whereby scholars produce research through creation. These methodologies span a wide range and are intrinsically interdisciplinary, but do share several features that make them useful for the purposes of this chapter, including the prioritization of "embodied knowledges" (P+K 117) over written research, more. Although terminological disputes proliferate, I will categorize these methodologies under the umbrella term of ‚Äòpractice as research,‚Äô a part of what David Whitton calls a "practical turn" in theater studies whereby creative work should be considered a "valid research process and/or a research outcome" (78). This practical turn is a controversial one, with both pragmatic and epistemological consequences associated with it; indeed, much of the literature on the topic citations focuses less on examples and more on how, and with what degree of success, practitioners have attempted to receive institutional recognition from the university for their research. 

