Importantly, though, my practice-based research is a series of adaptations rather than creations. This chapter, then, will be structured as a set of three experiments. I will begin each section with an explanation of the adapted text, with attention paid to what makes the text amenable to mechanical reproduction in the first place, and then move into an account of the process by which my adaptation was created as a way of drawing out features of the original texts. One of the guiding principles behind these adaptations is failure: although my goal is to do something that communicates some of what Beckett‚Äôs works do, something is inevitably lost in the translation from teleplay - or play - into what I‚Äôm going to loosely call a video game. 

