:: Case Study: THIS DISSERTATION
<h1>This Dissertation: A Preposterous Postmortem</h1>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 1">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 1 [pp nobr]
<p>I'm not sure, if I had to do it again, that I'd try writing my dissertation in Twine. I'm glad I have; the artifact I created as a result is different in kind from other dissertations, which is interesting, and the technical work I had to do to create it certainly helped me in my career, first at the MIT Digital Humanities Lab and second in my professional life as a product manager at a company that builds, among other things, nonlinear learning experiences.</p>
<p>However, some of the features that made Twine appealing to me initially ‚Äî the nonlinear structure, the robust support for digressions ‚Äî exacerbated issues I have as a scholar. The codex and the book can digress, but its structure does not lend itself to distraction in quite the same way.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 2">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 2 [pp nobr]
<p>The definitions and [[Glossary]] stand as the most obvious example of this. To make them worth clicking, they needed to contain both descriptive information and argumentative material that relates to the document's thesis. This meant, however, spending a lot of time writing a lot of material that a more casual reader might not read. It also raised some of the same kinds of sequencing issues that an endnote- or footnote-heavy document might have; if the information is crucial to the argument, then it really ought to be in the body of the document, and if it's not crucial, then it may not need to be there at all.</p>
<p>This, coupled with the document's general nonlinear structure, meant that I had less control over what the user had read at any given point in their reading. This had a negative impact, I think, on the conclusions of each case study; because so much argumentation and theoretical work was done off the main path, the conclusions were sometimes anticlimactic.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 3">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 3 [pp nobr]
<p>On the other hand, as I progressed in the document past the first chapter, I found the upside: because I'd already defined Benjamin's <span class="glow"><<define "aura" "Benjamin's aura">></span> in the case study on [[Ma Rainey's Black Bottom->Case Study: MA RAINEY'S BLACK BOTTOM]], I didn't need to define it again when discussing [[Her Story->Case Study: HER STORY]] ‚Äî and the fact that the definition was active in both sections did some of the work of connecting the disparate case studies that make up the three primary sections of the document.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 4">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 4 [pp nobr]
<p>Because this document is concerned with the specificity of particular media ‚Äî what possibilities a platform opens up, and which possibilities are closed ‚Äî it was important to me to take particular advantage of the possibilities afforded by Twine. For the interactivity to be meaningful, it had to fulfill certain requirements:</p>
<ol>
	<li>It had to engage the reader of the document in a way that would be difficult to achieve in a traditional book or codex;</li>
	<li>The mode of interactivity had to be connected to the object of study and to my argument in the case study;</li>
	<li>Some third requirement.</li>
</ol>
<p>You can rate how well each section's interactivity met each of these three goals on the forthcoming pages, which lays out how each case study is interactive, along with a reflection on its success or failure.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 5">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 5 [pp nobr]
<p>For <i>[[Blue Kettle->Case Study: BLUE KETTLE]]</i>, I wrote a custom macro to support the blockquotes from the text where <<blue "yes, like that">> and <<kettle "right, exactly, it toggles">> appear, allowing the user to toggle between the text and my best guess at the words replaced by the virus. This gives the case study a <<define "puzzle element">> ‚Äî or, at least, foregrounds the <<define "puzzle element">> that's already <<blue "there">> in the play, and about which the <<kettle "case">> study is focused. The <<blue "reader">> can play along, testing how well their <<kettle "decoding">> of the <<blue "text">> matches my own. A more <<blue "advanced">> version of this <<kettle "feature">> might use an alert pop-up to let the <<blue "reader">> <<kettle "type">> in their best <<blue "guess">>, and <<kettle "keep">> a <<blue "persistent">> <<kettle "score">>.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 6">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 6 [pp nobr]
<p>For <i>[[Achewood->Case Study: ACHEWOOD]]</i>, the embedded images and links were intended to mirror the web of sources that, together, make up the multimedia masculinity of its characters. By embedding the cookbooks, blogs, comic pages, and chatbots directly into the document, I intended to provide my reader with something like the experience of apprehending a character through so many different channels, within so many different genres. This was only so successful, and only took so much advantage of Twine itself. I think this is the weakest case study in the dissertation.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 7">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 7 [pp nobr]
<p>For <i>[[Ma Rainey's Black Bottom->Case Study: MA RAINEY'S BLACK BOTTOM]]</i>, the goal was to embed as much music as possible and useful into the experience. Because the play is so concerned with the recorded voice, there is both value and interest in providing a direct portal to Ma Rainey's actual voice. There's something provocative about using the voice of a dead woman whose recordings no longer belong to anyone when the case study's argument is about that ownership. Additionally, it dovetailed nicely into the introduction of my discussion about <i>36 Blackbirds</i> and <<define "technonecromancy">> more generally. With more time, I would have embedded the audio directly into the pages rather than requiring the user to pause their experience to listen.</p>

<<silently>><<set _next_passage to "Preposterous Postmortem 8">><</silently>>

:: Preposterous Postmortem 8 [pp nobr]
<p>For <i>Her Story</i>, I embedded clips from the actual game, along with audio, in an attempt to let people who hadn't played the game experience some version of what they were missing. Because the game is made up of fractured interviews, experienced nonlinearly through short video clips, I thought there was a neat parallel to be made by embedding linear, contained clips into the experience. A more talented programmer than me would have attempted to mimic the database quality of <i>Her Story</i> in the structure of the case study itself, but that was beyond my abilities. Still, the sound and visuals afforded by the embedded clips allows the reader to have a richer understanding of the game ‚Äî and, hopefully, of my argument.</p>

<p>I was also able to include a pair of 'definitions' here that worked to make the reader experience something like the transdiegetic identification that the case study explores. The definition for <span class= "definition-link"><<link "MURDER">><<murder>><</link>></span> isn't a definition at all; it's a jump scare of Mouth from <i>Not I</i>, meant to shock the reader and, by elevating their heart rate, pull them into the experience; similarly, the definition for <<define "mirror">> enables the user's camera and keeps the little green "recording" light on their laptop until they close the dissertation. Both cases are meant to make the user uncomfortable, and to bring them out of the position of a passive reading subject into something more active.</p>

